fileDesc.title: Sector Snap: Harrah's bid boosts casinos

NAF.raw:
Sector Snap: Harrah's bid boosts casinos
NEW YORK (AFX) - The majority of casino operators are trading higher Monday after Harrah's Entertainment Inc., the country's largest casino company, said it received a proposal from two private equity firms to acquire the company for $81 per share in cash.
Based on the company's 185.8 million shares outstanding, the offer from Apollo Management and Texas Pacific Group would be worth about $15.05 billion. The $81-per-share offer represents a 22 percent premium on the stock's closing price of $66.43 on Friday on the New York Stock Exchange. Shares of Harrah's soared on the news, jumping $9.17, or 13.8 percent, to $75.60 in morning trading on the New York Stock Exchange, nearing their 52-week high of $83.33. The stock has been trading in a range of $57.29 to $83.33 for the past 52 weeks. Shares of most casino companies were trading significantly higher on the news, with Penn National Gaming Inc., Ameristar Casinos Inc., Isle of Capri Casinos Inc. and Wynn Resorts Ltd. among the biggest movers. Boyd Gaming Corp.'s stock surged $2.28, or about 6 percent, to $40.75 on the Big Board on Harrah's news and a swap of Las Vegas assets with the casino operator. The stock has been trading in a 52-week range between $33.10 and $54.72. Copyright 2006 Associated Press. All rights reserved.
